This does not sound like a zbuffer-only problem, but rather like a
"can't-get-memory" problem. You most likely have the wrong driver
installer, or you have an rtg.library somewhere. Make sure that you have
the W3D_CyberGfx4(_PPC).library in your libs:Warp3D/GFXdrivers and nothing
else (i.e. two files only). Start Snoopdos while you start a demo and scan
for a OpenLib on "rtg.library" - if it openes OK, you have some old
Picasso96 installation still around, so the driver refuses to load.

If this does not work, check the version of your libraries (you can get a
run-down list of supported CyberGfx-Versions in the 3DWorld FAQ on Paul's
homepage), check the settings of your monitor and env variables, and make
sure that there is no rtg.library somewhere.

