They won't use H&P's emulator for their own announced Amiga emulation
environment. Currently it seems that nobody actually knows what emulator
they use, if they have written one themselves or are using some existing
one. All I know is that they were talking about their 68k emulators already
for years without ever having provided any single reference/information about
them.

Additionally it is currently unknown how they want to solve the problem
of cooperatively running Amiga-OS and QNX on the hardware without having
access conflicts. Either Amiga-OS runs in a virtual hardware environment,
or they try to separate Amiga-OS and QNX concerning hw access. The question
remains, how both should access floppies, serial port, parallel port, CIA's etc.
at the same time without conflicting eachother, if Amiga-OS isn't running
in a virtual environment. I don't expect QSSL to add special hacks to QNX/Neutrino allowing
for such cooperation, it would probably only mess up the QNX OS, which is
certainly the master concerning hardware access. More problems are certainly
there, such as the question how the interrupts are going to be shared between
the OSes. For me it looks quite messy to run two OS natively on the same
hardware, if no bottom layer is there, which provides hardware access to
multiple OSes. The other approach (virtual environment) would be a cleaner one,
but at least on AMIGA hardware Amiga-OS should be able to run on the real
hardware rather than only in a virtual environment.

In fact I have even some more general doubts about their whole emulation
environment at all. For those interested in WarpUp/Warp3D the Phase5 emulation
approach is no topic anyway.

