@node 07970.019
Subject: Re: Confusion over texture types
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Thu, 28 Oct 1999 13:06:00 +0000 (GMT)

On 27 Oct 1999, Tom Miles wrote:

> Basically how do all these types relate to iffs, gifs, jpegs, alpha
> channels etc?  The example code to convert a ppm file seem horribly
> complicated.  I'm sure with a bit of help I'll be able to sort all this
> out, this is after all one of a long line of problems which anyone who
> reads the c.s.a.programmer newsgroup will be well aware of :)

There is no relation between texture format and file format. The file
format is a representation of data on disk, while the different texture
formats are there to suit the different needs of 3D apps (e.g. space
consumption vs. texture quality).

The PPM loader in WarpTest does put in an alpha channel to get this groovy
transparency effect. You can ommit this, basically, after scanning the
header you can read width*height*3 bytes into the buffer, and use this
directly with W3D_R8G8B8 as a texture format. You might also want to check
out the Engine demo, as it can load PNG files, which are a bit more
compact.

Regards, Hans-Joerg.


