>I`m still in the dark about what system functions need to be changed from 68K
>code. Presumabley AllocVec becomes AllocVecPPC etc. but does all my code run
>on the PPC side appart from system calls to 68K functions (eg
>graphics.library)? or does the compiler need some kind of directive to tell
>it which bits are PPC and which are 68K?

For StormC this is simply achieved using the include files. For PPC libs
the prototype includes look different, and the compiler knows to generate
a PPC lib call instead of a 68K lib call. Of course the programmer itself
must explicitely name the function calls appropriately, so if you write
AllocVec() then the compiler will create a 68K call, even if there is a
PPC counterpart in powerpc.library.

For other compilers this difference is probably hidden in link libraries,
so if you call AllocVec, then some link lib will probably do the 68k
call, if you call AllocVecPPC, it will call the powerpc.library function.

To find out which calls to change to PPC you need a bit of experience.
Basically most system calls will remain the same, as powerpc.library
does only cover a sub-set of exec, timer.device and utility.library.
Usually you should convert memory allocation, semaphores, signals,
messsages, list, utility and timer functions (and maybe more). But
always check whether your application interfers with other 68k applications,
then the situation might become more difficult.

