Subject: Re: texture reducing in the distance
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Sat, 30 Oct 1999 23:08:14 +0000 (GMT)

On Sat, 30 Oct 1999, Wolfgang Krause wrote:

> Colud anyone give a more detailed explanation of this technique? Is this
> anything new in 3D programming or is it already used in games like Wipeout
> 2097 or Shogo? Would users of Blizzard PPC and BVision (like me) benefit
> from this technique used in games programming (especially speed wise)?

Shogo uses something like that. There are other tricks that can be done
that work similar. For example, Shogo removes the texture from an object
at a certain size of the triangle, and has quite good LOD information
stored in its model files.

Similarily, you can use linear maping only when the polygon is almost
facing you (i.e. the normal points almost straight towards the camera) and
it is not too close (this will increase performance on the ViRGE
especially, I am just building something like that into the Heretic II
renderer). 

But I think the most obvious thing should be LOD reduction, since this
will save calculations AND bus transfers, which is the MAJOR weakness of
current Amiga hardware!

Regards, Hans-Joerg.

